    "slug": "over-100-us-house-democrats-back-bill-to-cut-military-aid-to-israel",
    "summary": "More than 100 Democratic lawmakers in the US House of Representatives supported a bill to end $3.3 billion in annual military aid to Israel. The measure was ultimately defeated, but the vote signals growing divisions within the party over Israel policy.",
    "content": "A significant split within the US Democratic Party came into full view last week when more than 100 members of the House of Representatives voted in favor of a bill that would halt the annual $3.3 billion in military assistance the United States provides to Israel. The legislation was introduced by Republican Representative Thomas Massie, but drew support from a large bloc of Democrats, highlighting an intensifying debate over Washington's longstanding support for Israel.\n\nThe bill was ultimately defeated by a vote of 314 to 104, with a majority of Republicans and some Democrats opposing the measure. While the proposal failed, the 104 votes in favor represent a notable shift within Congress, as similar attempts in previous years garnered far less backing. Observers note that the growing support reflects changing attitudes among younger and more progressive lawmakers.\n\nThis development is particularly relevant for the Somali diaspora, which includes a significant Muslim and Arab population that has advocated for more balanced US foreign policy in the Middle East. Many diaspora members have watched closely as the Biden administration maintained traditional military aid levels despite calls from activist groups to condition or reduce assistance to Israel.\n\nThe vote also comes amid renewed violence in Gaza and the West Bank, which has galvanized pro-Palestinian movements worldwide. For Somalis in the diaspora, the issue resonates given Somalia's own history of conflict and its reliance on international aid. The outcome may influence diaspora political engagement, as community leaders weigh whether to support candidates who take a stronger stance on Israel policy.\n\nPolitical analysts say the 104 Democratic votes may embolden future efforts to attach conditions to military aid or redirect funds toward humanitarian assistance. The debate is expected to continue into the next congressional session, with implications for US foreign policy and diaspora advocacy.\n\nRead the original report from Goobjoog here: https://goobjoog.com/2026/07/16/mareykanka-in-ka-badan-100-xildhibaan-oo-dimuqraadi-ah-oo-taageeray-dhimista-gargaarka-milatari-ee-maraykanku-siiyo-israaiil/",
